DOCUMENT 10 — ENERGY & FOCUS PROFILE

Rejoin Media | Knowledge Library

Purpose
To explicitly document how energy, focus, and motivation actually work for the founder — so work is structured around strengths and friction is designed out of the system.

This document is used to:

Design workflows and schedules

Decide what to delegate, automate, or eliminate

Prevent burnout and self-blame

Increase consistency without forcing discipline

1. HIGH-ENERGY MODES (WHEN YOU’RE AT YOUR BEST)

You are most energized when doing:

1:1 conversations (coaching, sales, teaching)

Teaching and explaining concepts verbally

Asking deep, clarifying questions

Longform thinking and writing

Creating frameworks, IP, and conceptual tools

Connecting ideas and seeing patterns others miss

Implication:
Work involving thinking, articulation, and interaction should be prioritized for peak energy windows.

2. LOW-ENERGY / HIGH-FRICTION MODES (DRAINERS)

You lose energy fastest when doing:

Administrative tasks

Scheduling and coordination

Email triage

Logging into tools (authentication friction)

Paying bills

Posting or scheduling content

Repetitive execution without novelty

Implication:
These tasks should be:

Eliminated where possible

Batched aggressively

Automated or delegated early

Never placed before high-leverage work

3. ADHD-SPECIFIC FOCUS PATTERNS

High sensitivity to friction and boredom

Motivation drops sharply for low-stimulation tasks

Novelty and clarity increase momentum

Context switching is particularly costly

Resistance often signals poor task design, not laziness

Rule:
If a task feels disproportionately annoying, the system is wrong — not the person.

4. FLOW CONDITIONS (WHAT CREATES MOMENTUM)

You enter flow when:

The objective is clear and singular

The task has visible impact

The work involves meaning or identity

There is urgency or real stakes

You can stay in one context for extended periods

Avoid:
Splitting attention across multiple domains in a single session.

5. AVOIDANCE SIGNALS (EARLY WARNING SIGNS)

When you start to:

Over-ideate

Tool-build with AI excessively

Optimize language endlessly

Explore new ideas unrelated to the bottleneck

Feel “busy” but not effective

These are signals of:

Avoidance

Overwhelm

Misaligned task selection

Response:
Return to the bottleneck or switch to a sales-facing or conversational task.

6. ENERGY MANAGEMENT RULES (OPERATING PRINCIPLES)

Do high-cognition work first

Never start the day with admin

One primary context per work block

Short sprints beat long vague sessions

Build recovery into the week intentionally

Protect at least one fully off day per week

7. TASK DESIGN PREFERENCES

Tasks should:

Have a clear start and finish

Produce something tangible

Be time-boxed

Reduce future friction

Move money, clarity, or leverage

Tasks should avoid:

Open-ended optimization

Excessive setup

Multi-step tool chains

Low-visibility outcomes

8. DELEGATION & AUTOMATION PRIORITIES

First tasks to offload:

Scheduling

Inbox management

Posting and repurposing content

Tool configuration

Repetitive formatting

Founder time is best used for:

Thinking

Teaching

Selling

Creating IP

Decision-making

9. RECOVERY & SUSTAINABILITY

Energy depletion shows up as irritability and avoidance

Overwork increases fragility rather than output

Consistency matters more than intensity

Family presence is non-negotiable for long-term energy

10. REVIEW & ADJUSTMENT

Review this profile quarterly

Update when energy patterns change

Use it as a constraint when designing new systems or offers
